        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "[codex] Migrate Chrome companion to optional Native Messaging",
        "body": "## Summary\n\n- replace Chrome daemon loopback transport with an exact-extension-ID Native Messaging host\n- keep `nativeMessaging` optional and request it only from explicit Daemon enablement\n- add managed `daemonAllowed=false` UX plus fail-closed checks before permission requests and every native connection\n- preserve streaming, binary responses, models, logs, process views, chat, summaries, and slides through one bounded bridge\n- install/uninstall the macOS and Linux native host with `summarize daemon`; keep Direct and Browser modes daemonless\n- preserve configured Direct local providers on `localhost`/`127.0.0.1` while routing only known daemon operations through Native Messaging\n- document exact `ExtensionSettings.blocked_permissions`, per-ID `runtime_blocked_hosts`, `NativeMessagingBlocklist`, `NativeMessagingUserLevelHosts`, and managed-storage policies\n\n## Verification\n\n- `pnpm -s check`: 543 test files passed, 29 skipped; 2,906 tests passed, 43 skipped; 91.78% statement coverage\n- production Native Messaging Chromium E2E: passed (Chrome extension → installed native process → daemon health/auth/models/SSE → UI)\n- full Chromium compatibility suite: 106 passed, 5 intentional live-only skips\n- built Chrome manifest: `nativeMessaging` only in `optional_permissions`; no `<all_urls>`; scoped HTTPS, localhost, and IPv4 loopback grants\n- Direct local-provider Chromium E2E: summary and chat passed against `http://127.0.0.1:11434/v1` without daemon credentials\n- managed policy, permission denial, and fresh-install permission scenarios: passed\n- source-blind behavior validation: contract satisfied; no failures or blockers\n- Codex gpt-5.5 autoreview on the full rebased branch: clean, no accepted/actionable findings\n- Public Model Identifier Gate: passed; only public fixture identifiers are present\n\n## Product decisions / limitations\n\n- Windows Daemon mode still needs a packaged native-host `.exe`; the implementation deliberately does not add a weaker command-file or loopback-daemon workaround. Direct and Browser modes continue to work.\n- Removing required `<all_urls>` narrows privileged background HTTP fetches to HTTPS plus the explicit local-provider grants. Other cross-origin plain-HTTP media/assets are not guaranteed.\n- Enterprise deployments requiring no local HTTP should combine managed `daemonAllowed=false` with the documented exact-ID `runtime_blocked_hosts`; cloud Direct and ordinary Browser mode remain available.\n- The daemon remains a bearer-token HTTP service on loopback behind the native host. Native Messaging removes Chrome extension daemon-network access, but OS-authenticated local sockets would be a separate hardening project.\n",
        "branch": "codex/native-messaging-companion",
